{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_ferengi_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383345959/1930120301/0925.xml":{"full_text":"Ohio Farmer Uses Machinery to Raise Corn for 21 Cents a Bushel\nHAS QUIT WORRYING\nABOUT MART PRICES\nj BECAUSE OF SYSTEM\nPlanting Costs 22 Cents an\nAcre and Harvesting\n$1.14 per Acre\nAVERAGE YIELD 60 BUSHELS\nActual Expenditures for Gas,\nOil, Labor, and Repairs\nIncluded\nLarue, Ohio, Dec. 3.\u2014t/Pi\u2014C. T.\nGuthery. a farmer of Larue, says the\nprice of corn is of little concern lo\nhim. He has learned to produce it\nat a total cost of only 21 cents a\nbushel.\nHe does it on a mass production\nbasis\u2014pic wing, planting and harvest*\ning by machinery.\nIt costs him 62 cents an acre to\nplow, he says, pulling three 18-inch\nplows at the rate of one and one-half\nacres an hour. Preparation of the\nseed bed, done by a combination of\ntools which cover two and one-half\nto three acres an hour, costs 48 cents\nan acre.\nPlanting costs 22 cents an acre and\nharvesting, including cribbing, costs\n$1.14 an acre.\nInterest, Taxes Included\nThe costs enumerated, Guthery\nsays, are actual expenditures for\nlabor, gas. oil. and repair on the im\nplements. In figuring his total cost\nof 21 cents a bushel he includes culti\nvation. interest and tax on the land;\ninterest, taxes, depreciation and up\nkeep on the machinery, as well as\ncost of seed and fertilizer.\n\"It requires only four and a half\nman hours for us to raise an <-cre of\ncorn.\u2019* he says, \"and our average yield\nis 60 bushels to the acre.\"\n\u201cDon't worry about the market.\u201d\nhe advises. \u201cThat's no longer a source\nof complaint with me in corn grow\ning.\u201d\nGuthery uses three planters in a\nsingle unit, covers five rows at a time\nat the rate of seven acres an hour\nwith the rotary hoe and pulls a wagon\nalong with his one-row picker to\ngather the corn without extra labor\nand power.\nProm other sections of the coni\nbelt come reports of sympathetic lean\ning to the theory, advanced by the\nfarm board for one. that agricultural\nprofits may depend as much on a\nlower cost of production as on a rise\nin prices.\nMust Be Used Right\nAn lowa farmer, using six and\neight-horse hitches, produced corn for\na total outlay of 21 \u2018i man-hours an\nacre. Use of labor depends consider\nably. however, on how it is employed\nand the number of operations com\npleted.\nWhereas one lowa farmer produced\ncorn, up to the period of harvesting,\nat a cost of 2.8 man hours an acre, 2\ntractor hours and 3.2 horse hours,\nanother used 6 man hours 4.2 tractor\nhours and 4.8 horse hours.\nBettering Guthery\u2019s four and one\nhalf man hours an acre including\nharvesting. Is the record of an lowa\nfarmer who, using motor equipment\nentirely, spent only 3.6 man hours an\nacre on his corn as compared to 300\nman hours an acre where all oper\nations were performed by hand.\nI PEOPLE\u2019S FORUM I\nV\nEditor the Tribune:\nIn your issue of Nov. 17 there ap\npeared In the Forum an article by\none Mr. Independent of Dickinson.\nThis article criticised severely the\nlate consolidation of banks. This\nwriter has no knowledge of the bank\ning business but believes that the men\ni representing the various banks that\n5 ffiliated with those of the Twin\nCities fully appreciated the advant\nages they would derive by such a\nconsolidation. If we scan the list of\nhese banks, so consolidating, we find\nthem to be the largest and most sub\nstantial institutions in their respec\ntive communities. The men who are\nmanaging them have been connected\nfrith these institutions for many years\nand have, by their wise management,\ncarried on the business over many\npitfalls of some very difficult periods.\nThey have scrupulously guarded\ntheir depositor\u2019s interests, and gain\ned the public\u2019s unqualified confidence.\nIt is therefore unwarranted to im\npeach their integrity. But it is\nhuman to find fault and condemn\nothers and this is frequently done by\npeople who have no interest at all,\nto protect.\nThis consolidation represents a cap\nital of nearly one billion dollars, a\nstupendous sum of money. The\nmorel and financial interest, scatter\ned throughout the northwest, is bound\nto strengthen its future prosperity.\nThere is an old saying: \u201cWhat\u2019s good\nfor the goose is also good for the\ngander.\u201d With the headquarters being\nlocated in the Twin Cities, the gate\nway to this immense empire, it can\nnot help but spell an important future\nfor the northwest, just as the terri\ntory of Chicago and that of Kansas\nCitv are benefited by those hustling\nand great centers. Just so, can we\nlook forward to an era of new de\nvelopment. But we have, and are\nmaking mistakes, and often we wan\nder about aimlessly In darkness, but\nafter all the true test lies in our\nability to overcome our faults, to en\ndure and survive the trials and dis\nappointments which confront us in\nour daily life and emerge triumph\nant.\nInto all lives, I think, sad, dis\ncouraging times will come, times when\none needs something outside one\u2019s\nself; to lift one\u2019s self. The people of\nNorth Dakota have so much to be\n'thankful for, if they only would ad\nmit it. Let us take the people In the\nindustrial centers with their dirty\nstreets and the noise, with crowds\nof hurried and tired people. One\nwalks for one hour, two hours amid\nsuch scenes and goes home to one's\nhouse more weary and tired and sick\nof life than when one started out.\nHow gloriously different it is here,\nbut we don\u2019t seem to realize it nor\nappreciate it. Jt is known fart that\nMau people will grumble and kick\nMotorized corn plcker-husker (above) Is part of power equipment used by C. T. Guthery, Larue, Ohio, farmer.\nto cut cost of producing com to 21 cents a bushel.\nall the time. They would kick if\nthey were to enter Paradise. Business\ndepressions rim in cycles. If we turn\na leaf or two back in history we will\nfind it so. Business, just like the\nhuman system, will get sick, when one\nwill lose all thought of going ahead.\n\u201cA supreme intelligence\u201d gives us\nperiodical pause, but after such a\npause all Ills seem to disappear like\nmagic and a feeling of irresistible\nvigor creeps into our blood without\nour own effort. It is natural that it\nshould be so. Just as the storm\nbrings darkness, so the earth shines\nwith a much brighter green, with a\nnew sun. We can not control the\nmind, so as to picture the betterment\nahead. We grope in darkness even\nthough the sunlight be just beyond\nthe veil of a darkened \u201cmind.\u201d But\nit is perhaps best that it should bo\nso. Business, like the system, will\nimprove in health and vigor and be\ncome much better than before\u2014it\nlias always been thus. Alexander of\nMacedonia was told by the Oracle\n\"He, that unties the Gordian knot\nwill conquer Asia\u201d Alexander cut the\nGordian knot and conquered Asia.\nNow if the business depression is the\nGordian knot, let us cut it. and the\nsooner conquer our difficulties. Alex\nander demonstrated his strong will\npower. Let us. every body without\nexception, demonstrate ours and all\nour troubles will quickly disappear.\nWe shall realize that Just in a little\nwhile growth has been resumed and\nabsolutely no limit to our possibilities\nappear. The gentleman. Mr. Inde\npendent of Dickinson, will also find a\nfield for usefulness as wide as his\ntalents and strength.\nSincerely yours.\nElgin. N. D.. Nov. 20, 1930.\nEditor Bismarck Tribune:\nI see by the papers that Fargo and\nthe \u201cFoolem\" crowd are up to their\nold tricks of trying to hog everything\nthat comes into North Dakota. Their\nlatest move was to try to put the Bis\nmarck radio station, KFYR, out oi\ncommission for the benefit of the\nFargo station, WDAY, which I sup\npose would like to have North Da\nkota all to itself.\nIt was lucky for us radio fans out\nhere on the Missouri Slope that the\nfederal radio commission stepped in\nto support its own order granting\nthe Bismarck station additional power.\nHie people of southwestern North Da\nkota have become very strongly at\ntached to station KFYR, and this at\ntempt bp the Fargo crowd to retard\nits growth is greatly resented out\nhere, especially by the business men\nand farmers whose wave-lengths of\nmemory are not so short but what they\ncan remember a few old scores against\nFargo that have never been fully\nsettled.\nThe farmers have never forgotten\nhow the Fargoans tried to chase our\nfirst organized Equity crowd out of\ntown, and how the Fargo Forum has\nalways supported and continues to\nsupport the grain combine.\nAnd I wonder if the wholesale and\nretail merchants from this part of\nNorth Dakota wouldn\u2019t have some\nthing interesting to tell about freight\nOUTOUK WAY\ny*v -;r.'Sr n\nMachine Production Boosts Corn Profits\nPit L I I r~ fi*\nBRICGt\nArticle No. 68\nBy WM. K. McKENNEY j 1\nSecretary American Bridge League i\nMany times the opening lead will!\nmake it possible for the declarer to j,\nget a clear picture of the hands held i j\nby his opponents and will assist him!-\nin making an extra trick. 1\nNORTH i\nS\u2014lo-6-9-3 I\nWEST H\u20149-8-4 EAST 1\nio 7. o\u2014o*9*2 c K-j-\nM c-o-m\nH\u2014MO-7 H-A-K-2\nD\u2014A*4 o\u2014K*J* 1\nC-J.0.5* 10-6* J\n3 SOUTH\u2014 DEALER c _ 3 j\nS\u2014o I\nH\u2014Q-6-5-3\no\u2014B*7-5\nC-A-10-9-72\nThe Bidding I\nAt contract. South would pass. West 1\npass. North pass, and East would open\nthe bidding with one diamond. The\nSouth hand is too weak to overcall 1\nand should pass. West denies diamond\nsupport by bidding one no trump.\nEast jumps to three no trump, which\ncloses the contracting.\nThe Play\nNorth has the opening lead and aa\nthe only four-card suit he holds is\nspades, he opens with the three spot.\nBy applying the rule of eleven, the\ndeclarer knows that the South hand\nholds only one spade higher than the\nthree, therefore the four Is played\nfrom the dummy, South playing the\nqueen and declarer winning with the\nace.\nDeclarer returns the deuce of\nspades and finesses the* eight spot In\ndummy which holds the trick, South\nA. ARNTSON.\nBismarck, N. D.\nrates if they cared to go into the rec\nords. Fargo has for years had an un\nfair advantage over the cities in west\nern North Dakota In commodity rates,\nand this will continue as long as our\npeople are willing to submit to Fargo\ndomination. To many of them the\nFargo Foolem is still a textbook and\ngospel.\nIn business as well as in politics\nwestern North Dakota has had to\nfight its battles against open as well\nas secret opposition from Fargo. Can\nwe expect anything better in the fu\nture? Hardly!'\nFargo bears watching.\nC. K. NELSON,\nJamestown, N. D., Dec. 3.\u2014 (JP)\nMrs. Evva Sollen was elected presl\ndent of the Jamestown Degree ot\n'-Honor Monday night.\nMRS. SOLIEN ELECTED\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE. WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 3, 1930\nshows his ace of clubs by discarding\nthe seven of clubs. The jack of dia\nmonds la returned from dummy.\nWhen Soqth plays the five, the de\nclarer goes up with the ace and re\nturns the four spot, finessing the ten.\nThe king Is returned and declarer dis\ncards a small club. Dummy continues\nwith the six of diamonds, South com\npletes his club echo by playing the\ndeuce, declarer discards the seven of\nspades. North discarding the six of\nspades.\nThe last diamond is led from dum\nmy, South drops the six of hearts,\ndeclarer the nine of spades and North\nthe ten of spades. Dummy's next lead\nIs the king of spades, South Is forced\nto protect the heart suit and must\ndiscard the nine of clubs, declarer dis\ncarding the five of clubs. The Jack of\nspades is led from dummy and South\nis forced to discard the ten of clubs,\ndeclarer sheds the six of clubs and\nNorth the four of hearts.\nThe declarer has a perfect count on\nthe South hand. He knows that South\noriginally held one spade and three\ndiamonds and he undoubtedly held\nfive clubs to the ace and four hearts.\nThe declarer leads the king of clubs\nfrom dummy, throwing South in the\nlead and forcing him to lead a heart.\nThe declarer need not worry where\nthe queen of hearts Is. If North holds\nit, declarer would cover the heart lead\nwith the jack and ffirce North\u2019s queen.\nBy correctly reading the hand, de\nclarer has made a small slam at no\ntrump, but as only three were bid,\nhe scores 105 for tricks bid and 50\neach for the threfe overtricks. No slam\nbonus is scored as the slam was not\nbid.\n(Copyright, 1930, NEA Service, Ine.)\nSix Selected for\nDebate Squad at U\nGrand Fbrks, N. D\u201e Dec. 3.\u2014Six\nmen were selected from a field of 22\ncandidates as additions to the de\nbating squad of the University of\nNorth Dakota, Monday, according to\nWilliam Schrier. coach.\nHarold Cram, Minot; Kenneth\nKjos, New Rockford; Kermit John\nson. Warwick; Oswald Tufte, Coop\nerstown; Richard Ross, Grand Forks;\nand Odin Ramsland, Grace City; sur\nvived the eliminations consisting of\nfour-minute speeches.\nHie squad also contains seven men\ni remaining from the last year\u2019s squad.\n;All new members of the team had\nj previous experience in debating.\nBy Williams\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\ncontinues wry\nGood .Mingleg With Bad in\nWeekly Report Issued by\nBusiness Survey Firm\nFavorable items continue to mingle\nwith those less favorable in the week\nly business outlook issued today by\nR. G. Dun Co\nThe survey follows:\nIn the absence of new phases of\noutstanding prominence, the main in\nterest in business circles now centers\nin the probable developments beyond\nthe short period remaining this year.\nVariations in the volume of current\ntrade largely reflect seasonal forces\nand are not of great Importance, the\nreally significant movements being\nthose with a fundamental bearing on\nfuture trends. The recent moderate\ngains in some quarters have afforded\na measure of encouragement, but an\nappraisal of general conditions dearly\nshows that widespread recovery is yet\nto be achieved. Frequent reiteration of\nthe statement that many commit\nments are being deferred reveals a\nclose adherence to the policy of cau\ntion growing out of far-reaching eco\nnomic changes, but disappointment\nover results in different lines has\narisen partly because of the expecta\ntion of more rapid revival than the\nfacts of the situation justified. A sharp\nand sweeping decline in wholesale\nquotations naturally has been a dis\nturbing Influence everywhere, and the\nreadjustment to an altered basis of\nconsumption, production and prices\ncould not be quickly completed. Re\ntrenchment and discrimination In\nbuying, with a distinct preference\nshown, for the more staple and useful\nmerchandise, is among -the -evidences\nof the diminished public purchasing\npower caused by unusually low prices\nfor agricultural products and unem\nployment of workers in Industrial cen\nters. The transition to a sounder basic\nstatus, however, has been proceeding\nsteadily, and the point has been\nreached where a more confident view\nof the prospects appears to be war\nranted. In a statistical way, compar\nisons with the records of a year ago\ncontinue to be unfavorable, but much\nhas been accomplished since that time\nin the elimination of weak spots, and\nin this respect the outlook is im\nproved. Annual inventorying soon to\nbegin or in progress now 1$ being\ncounted upoq to disclose.a stronger\nposition In many instances. The ac\ntion of securities markets has been\nmore reassuring, deflation of specu\nlative loans has been drastic, and\nmoney rates are exceptionally easy.\nHence, next to the last month of this\nyear is closing with a number of por\ntents whose ultimate effects cannot\nfail to be beneficial.\nBurleigh Group to\nPlan Farm Program\nConsideration of the 1931 agricul\nture program will be the principal\npurpose of Burleigh county\u2019s agricul\nture committee at their,. conference\nDec. 4 in the Association of Commerce\nrooms, according to County Agent H.\nC. Putnam. N. D. Gorman, state coun\nty agent leader, will give the main\naddress.\nCommittees appointed to help with\nthe program are: George Will, Bis\nmarck, chairman; Tyler Johnson, Ster\nling, hogs; Walter Sellens, Bismarck,\nbeef cattle; P. P. Bliss, McKensie,\nsheep; Enoch Anderson, Baldwin, feed\nand pasture; Mrs. P. P. Bliss, Mc-\nKensie, clothing; Mrs. A. E. Kopplin,\nWing, home management; P. M. Gos\nney, Sterling, dairy cattle; E. W. An\nderson, McKenzie, farm power; Mrs.\nEnochson, Mofflt, nutrition; L. E.\nHeaton Jr., McKensie, farm manage\nment; J. M. Thompson, Wilton, horti\nculture; A. J. Norlin, Menoken, cash\ncrops; and Anthony Erickson, Wilton,\npoultry.\nCounty Agent H. C. Putnam will be\nsecretary of the general committee.\ni AT THE MOVIES\n\nCAPITOL THEATRE\nAnother Broadway stage star to mi\ngrate to the screen is Barbara Stan\nwyck who plays a leading role in\n\u201cMexicali Rose,\u2019\u2019 the Columbia all\ntalking film of the colorful Mexican\nborder life, coming to the Capitol\ntheatre tomorrow. .This <is ..her sec\nond screen appearance. \u201et-\nBarbara Stanwyck, recruited for the\nstage from the New York night clubs,\nproved the sensation of.the theatrical\nseason when she made'her debut as\nthe heroine in \u201cBurlesque.\u2019? Her work\nin this play stamped her as one of\nAmerica\u2019s leading actresses.\nHer role in \u201cMexicali Rose\u2019\u2019 is a\ncolorful one. admirably suited to her\nvivid personality. Sam Hardy ap\npears opposite her.\nPARAMOUNT THEATRE\n\u201cGirl of the Golden West,\u2019\u2019 which\nconies to the Paramount Theatre\ntomorow as a First National and Vi\ntaphone production, is considered\nDavid Belasco\u2019s outstanding thea\ntrical success, and it placed him defi\nnitely in the forefront of American\nplay producers.\nThe play opened tn 1905. was\ngiven its first tryout performance in\nthe Belasco Theatre in Pittsburgh.\nIt was so popular that it was im\nmediately taken in to New York\nCity, where it ran to capacity au\ndiences during that and the follow\ning season.\nIt then went on \u201cthe road,\u2019\u2019 where\nit repeated its New York success.\nIt is still considered one of the\nmost popular plays of repertory com\npanies. Practically every stock com\npany of note has played i: at one\ntime or another.\nOthers in the original stage cast\nincluded James Kirkwood. Lowell\nSherman, Robert Wllllard, T. Haynes\nHunter, John W. Cope and Horace\nJames. Ann Harding. James Rennie,\nand Harry Bannister play the lead\ning redes in the new talking picture\nversion.\nDE COURCY KEEPS HAT ON\nLondon. Dec. 3. ijf) Michael\nCharles Cameron Claremont Constan\ntine d\u00ab Courcy. who has just been\nchristened, can keep his hat on in the\npresence of the king. An ancestor. Sir\nJ&hn <ie Courcy. in the twelfth cen\ntury. fought for England in single\ncombat with a representative of\nPrance. The Frenchman was routed.\nSir John obtained the right for his\nsuccessors to remain covered before\nfuture kings.\nPrince of Wales Selected Her to Play in\nHis Show\nHer beauty found royal favor when H. R. H. the Prince of Wales was seek\ning talent for the tableau staged for the benefit of Ida personal fund for\nthe British Legion. Lady Moira Combe, shown here in her latest portrait,\nwas selected by the prince to take a leading part In the revue, which was\nheld in the London pavilion.\nCROP PRODUCTION AND PRICE\nFOR LAST 2 YEARS COMPARED\nAgricultural College Export Estimates That Livestock Has\nGained Big Advantage Over Grains at Result\nof Prico Changes\nComparisons between crop production and prices received by fanners in\n1930 and 1929 are contained in a statistical study Issued by Rex E. Willard,\nfarm management demonstrator for the state agricultural college at Fargo.\nThe production data are taken from reports by the Untied States de\npartment of agriculture and the prices used are the average farm prices\nreceived by North Dakota producers on October 15 of the respective years.\nSince data on poultry and eggs are meager, the report includes no quan\ntities for these items, and the total value is not estimated for this reason.\nThe dairy products listed Include only creamery butter.\nWillard estimates that the total value of agricultural production for 1929.\nexcluding feed for livestock, which is represented by the stock, was\n$206,246,000, compared with $131,319,000 for 1930, or a decrease of 37 per cent.\nThe value of grain decreased 43 per cent, and of livestock and its products\n26 per cent The decrease of 26 per cent in the price of feeds reduces livestock\ncosts and results in a further advantage for livestock as compared with\ngrain, Willard asserts.\nThe table of production and prices follows:\nAmount Price Value Amount Price Value\n000 bu. 000 bu.\nWheat 93.396 f 1.11 9103,670,000 96,923 $0.67 $55,246,000\nRye 8,416 .80 6,732,000 10,470 .80 3,141,000\nFlax 6,876 3.01 20,697,000 10,675 1.52 16.326.000\nBarley 34.960 .42 14,683,000 39,392 .29 11,424,000\nOats 33,768 .34 11,481,000 37,530 .22 8,254,000\nCorn 16,884 .74 12,124,000 17,684 .67 11,781,000\n000 tons 000 tone\nTame hay 1,529 8.67 13,256,000 1,543 7.47 11,526,000\n000 bu. 000 bu.\nPotatoes 6,960 1.40 9,744,000 7,350 .95 6,881,000\n000 ton\u00df 000-tons\nWild hay 957 .0.50 6,220,000 1;181 5.70 6,782,000\n000 lbs. 000 lbs.\nWool 5,219 .28 1,461,000, 5,480 .16 877.000\nDairy products 39,077 .44 17,194,000\n000 cars 000 Cart\nCattle 11,657 8.10 20,595.000' 12.697 5.30 14,805,000\nHogs 10,7028.20 14,919,000 10,167 7.80 13,481,000\nLambs 1,525 10.70 2,774,000 1,601 6.00 1,633,000\nSheep 508 6.30 544,000 533 3.20 290,000\nChickens 161 ...,t .124\nEggs 28 19\nTurkeys 25 .23\nHoney x 675,000 600,000\nStudents Will Honor\nLate University Dean\nGrand Forks, N. D.; Dec. 3.\u2014-Ar\nrangements for a memorial convoca\ntion paying tribute to Dean Vernon\nP. Squires, late dean of the liberal\narts college of the University of North\nSail Two Oceans in Tiny Canoe\nTwice given up for lo6t at sea and twice the object, of intendve search by\nthe coast guard when they were long overdue, these two intrepid Germans\nwho are trying to sail a canoe from San Francisco to Uruguay have reached\nLos Angeles with 500 miles of water behind them. They were in several\nstorms and only escaped perishing by a hair\u2019s breadth. With their canoe\nin \u201cdrydock.\u201d fts shown here. they ware resting preparatory to starting the\nnext leg of their long journey to Uruguay. The man in the dark suit is\nMax Relk; the one attired in white Is Frederick Pohi. The msp shows\ntheir route.\nDakota, are being completed to allow\nthe program to be presented Decem\nber 11, John E. Howard, convocation\nchairman, said Friday.\nNegotiations to obtain Judge W. F.\nNuessle of Bismarck and a promi\nnent university alumnus' as speakers\nare under way. chrol M. Humpstone\nwill handle special musical numbers.\nMercer Woman Is\nDead at McClusky;\nMcClusky, N. D., Dec. \u00bb.\u2014Edith\nThompson, 24, of Mercer, died In Mc-\nClusky at 1:30 o\u2019clock Monday a ttes?\nnoon. Death was caused by tubercu\nlous meningitis.\nFuneral services will be held this\nweek and interment .will be made\nat Mercer.\nMcClusky Lions Have\nLadies Night Festival\nMcClusky. N. D., Dec. 3. \u2014Ladles\u2019\nnight was observed by the McClusky\nLions club Monday to take the place\nof the regular luncheon meeting for\nthat day.\nA banquet for Lions and their lady\nand other guests, numbering\n78. was held at the Moore hotel dining\nroom at 7:15 p. m.\nThe Misses Pearl Winter and An\ntoinette Finstad played a piano duet.\nA vocal solo was given by Miss Mabel\nErickson. Herman Peters entertained\nwith a chalk talk. The feature of the\nprogram, however, was the witty\nstories told about the individual\nLions and few if any escaped the\nbanter of the entertainment com\nmittee.\nBoyle Would Amend\nFarm Marketing Act\nChicago. Dec. 3.\u2014 (JP) \u2014Calling upon\ncongress to amend the farm market\ning act Immediately so that the gov\nernment will be taken \u201cout of the\nmarket as buyer, seller, and specu\nlator,\u201d Prof. James E. Boyle, of Cor\nnell university, vigorously denounced\nactivities of the federal farm board\nIn an address delivered here today\nbefore the American Association of\nCreamery Butter manufacturers.\nDr. Boyle described the present\nmethod of \u201ctrying to influence prices\nby withdrawing the surplus from the\nmarket and withholding It till a later\ndate\u201d has been proven disastrous by\nthe program tried in Brazil coffee.\nSCHOOL NOTES\nWING\n(Kieth giving topic in English)\n\u201cAfter the boy had finished the\nairplane, we went for a ride. He\nflew up and landed down.\u201d\nLeonard Knowles is out for basket\nball practice.\nMr. Wagle (asking questions in\nPresent Day Problems).,\nMr. Wagle: Olga, what is watered\nstock?\nOlga: Stock with no stable behind\nit.\nOladys Rue. a rural school teacher\nof our vicinity spent Tuesday with\nus.\nArthur Weber is staying in town\nbecause of bad roads.\nPrank Farley is certainly speedy,\nhe made two and a quarter miles in\nan hour on horseback. He faced the\nblizzard Tuesday.\nIn Early History class, we were\nreading about Julius Caesar studying\nthe life of Alexander the Great Ju\nlius Caesar wept because Alexander\nhad conquered the world and he\nhadn\u2019t done anything.\nMiss McGinnis said. \u201cIt would be\nfunny if one of our boys cried about\nthat.\u201d\nWillard spoke up, \u201cI have done a\nlot of things but they aren\u2019t on rec\nord yet.*\u2019\nPrimary Notes\nLinda Banttari and Rosa Horner\nhad 100 per cent in spelling for the\nweek.\nThe Second graders are making\nbooklets about the Pilgrims.\nViola Barth\u2019s birthday was last\nWednesday.\nMary Jane Olson is back in school.\nShe had the measles.\nDorothy and Carl Edwards are ab\nsent from school because of the\nmeasles.\nHenry Banttari and John Fields\nwere absent from school Tuesday.\nHelen Harty was absent Tuesday\nbecause of a cold.\nThe eighth grade had an arithmetic\ntest Monday.\nWhile playing Monday Ellen Mae\nHubbell fell and broke her right arm.\nShe was taken to Wilton that evening\nfor medical treatment.\nI Today\u2019s Congress\nBB\\ATR\nReceives President Hoover\u2019s budget\nmessage.\nTakes up Oouzen* bill for federal\nregulation of interstate motorbus\nlines.\nMuscle Shoals conference commit\ntee meets.\nCampaign funds committee takes\nup new reports of Pennsylvania ex\npenditures.\nHOI SR\nReceives budget message.\nBegins general debate on the treas\nury-postoffice appropriation bill.\nJudiciary committee holds executive\nhearing on Investigation of federal\njudges.\nBOY\u2019S ARM INJURED\nJamestown. N. D.. Dec. 3.\u2014(JP;\nRobert Leslie, whose left hand and\narm were mangled in a feed grinder\nat a Woodworth elevator Saturday,\nwas reported resting easily st a hos\npital here today. His hand and part\nof the arm were amputated.\nJAMESTOWN NURSE DIES\nJamestown. N. D.. Dec. 3.\u2014(/P\u00bb-\nSister Frederick, nurse at Trinity\nhospital here, died yesterday after an\nextended illness. She came here in\n1925 from the St. Joseph Novitiate,\nSt. Paul. Minn., and had been sta\ntioned at the hospital since.\nSTICKERS\nThe above sketch can be divided, by\ntwo straight lines, so as to make two\npieces of one pattern, the same size and\nshape, and two pieces of another pattern,\nalso the same size and shape. Can you\nflrt it)\n(Stickler Solution on Editorial Page)\nJl","height":"29319","width":"22638"}}
